## Create a Power Schedule

```shell
curl -XPOST "<%= curl_url %>/api/power-schedules" \
  -H "Authorization: BEARER <%= curl_token %>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
  "schedule": {
    "name": "business hours only",
    "description": null,
    "enabled": true,
    "scheduleType": "power",
    "scheduleTimezone": "UTC",
    "unit": "minute",
    "sundayOn": 0,
    "sundayOff": 0,
    "mondayOn": 420,
    "mondayOff": 1140,
    "tuesdayOn": 420,
    "tuesdayOff": 1140,
    "wednesdayOn": 420,
    "wednesdayOff": 1140,
    "thursdayOn": 420,
    "thursdayOff": 1140,
    "fridayOn": 420,
    "fridayOff": 1140,
    "saturdayOn": 0,
    "saturdayOff": 0,
    "enabled": true
  }
}'
```

> The above command returns JSON structured like getting a single power schedule: 

### HTTP Request

`POST <%= api_url %>/api/power-schedules`

### JSON Parameters

Parameter | Default | Description
--------- | ------- | -----------
name      |  | A name for the power schedule
description      |  | A description for the power schedule
scheduleType      |  | Type of schedule: Power (power), Power Off (power off)
scheduleTimezone      | UTC | Time Zone eg. America/New_York, Europe/Amsterdam, etc.
enabled      | true | Enabled
sundayOn | 0 | Sunday Start minute of the day
sundayOff | 1440 | Sunday End minute of the day
mondayOn | 0 | Monday Start minute of the day
mondayOff | 1440 | Monday End minute of the day
tuesdayOn | 0 | Tuesday Start minute of the day
tuesdayOff | 1440 | Tuesday End minute of the day
wednesdayOn | 0 | Wednesday Start minute of the day
wednesdayOff | 1440 | Wednesday End minute of the day
thursdayOn | 0 | Thursday Start minute of the day
thursdayOff | 1440 | Thursday End minute of the day
fridayOn | 0 | Friday Start minute of the day
fridayOff | 1440 | Friday End minute of the day
saturdayOn | 0 | Saturday Start minute of the day
saturdayOff | 1440 | Saturday End minute of the day


